## I. The Memo

On August 23, 1971, Lewis F. Powell Jr. — a corporate attorney, a board member of Philip Morris, a former president of the American Bar Association, and a man who had spent his career in the White male social and corporate elite of Richmond, Virginia — mailed a confidential memorandum to his friend Eugene B. Sydnor Jr., chairman of the Education Committee of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. The memo was titled “Attack on American Free Enterprise System.” It was eight pages long. Two months later, on October 22, 1971, President Richard Nixon nominated Powell to the Supreme Court. The memo was not disclosed to the Senate during his confirmation proceedings. Powell was sworn in as an Associate Justice on January 7, 1972 — less than six months after delivering the document that would reshape the architecture of American power for half a century and beyond.

Powell’s argument was straightforward in its diagnosis and sweeping in its prescription. The American economic system, he wrote, was under broad attack — not merely from extremists of the left but from “perfectly respectable elements of society”: the college campus, the pulpit, the media, the intellectual and literary journals, the arts and sciences, and from politicians. He identified Ralph Nader’s consumer protection movement — which had triggered the American consumer movement after Nader’s 1965 exposé *Unsafe at Any Speed* put a focus on the auto industry putting profit ahead of safety — as the chief antagonist. Powell’s experiences as a corporate lawyer and a director on the board of Philip Morris made him a champion of the tobacco industry who railed against the growing scientific evidence linking smoking and cancer. The civil rights movement had disrupted Jim Crow across the South, drawing out and exposing the racist violence that had long enforced segregation and upsetting America’s all-White corporate suites and boardrooms. Anti-war protesters derided Dow Chemical’s manufacture of napalm and scorned the military-industrial complex. Women’s rights protesters challenged all-male corporate management structures. The environmental movement protested chemical leaks, toxic products, and the poisons belching from corporate smokestacks. Public health groups began linking the tobacco industry to deadly illnesses and lead paint companies to brain damage in children.

Powell saw all of this as an existential threat to the free enterprise system. The overall tone of his memo reflected a widespread sense of crisis among elites in the business and political communities. His response was not a single campaign but an ecosystem — a multi-decade, multi-institutional project to capture the commanding heights of American public life.

He called for the creation of a permanent intellectual infrastructure: a “faculty of scholars” who could be deployed to campuses and deployed against hostile academic voices, speakers’ bureaus to carry the corporate message, and the monitoring of textbooks and television content. He advocated “constant surveillance” of national television networks, arguing that this applied “not merely to so-called educational programs (such as ‘Selling of the Pentagon’), but to the daily ‘news analysis’ which so often includes the most insidious type of criticism of the enterprise system.” He urged the Chamber to insist on the right to be heard, on “equal time,” and to deploy “whatever degree of pressure — publicly and privately — may be necessary.” This would be “a long road,” Powell warned, “and not for the fainthearted.”

Powell understood that the project required institutional capture across multiple domains simultaneously. He identified the judiciary as “perhaps the most important instrument for social, economic, and political change,” citing the ACLU as a liberal entity that had experience promoting the appointment of sympathetic judges, and called for a similarly equipped conservative organization to take up the cause on behalf of business. In his section titled “The Neglected Political Arena,” he recommended using political influence to stem “the stampedes by politicians to support any legislation related to ‘consumerism’ or to the ‘environment’” — placing the word “environment” in derogatory quotation marks. He wrote that political power “is necessary; it must be assiduously cultivated; and when necessary, it must be used aggressively and with determination — without embarrassment and without the reluctance which has been so characteristic of American business.”

He recognized that “the entire program” required an active and aggressive media presence and the utmost care in brand management. Powell understood that long-term, lasting change required appealing to the hearts and minds of the public at large. He advised that all channels of communication had “to meet the most exacting standards of accuracy and professional excellence” so that the views they advocated would carry the weight of credibility.

The memo was not the work of a fringe thinker. It was, as the Washington and Lee University archive describes it, both credited as having “changed America” and the single most requested document in the Lewis F. Powell Jr. Papers. Senator Sheldon Whitehouse, in his “Scheme” series of Senate floor speeches, described the memo as the origin point of “a long-running, right-wing scheme to capture the Supreme Court” through dark money — “hundreds of millions of dollars in anonymous hidden spending.” The Alliance for Justice’s 1993 report *Justice for Sale* mentioned it prominently. The case for the memo being a seminal document in the neoconservative movement was made in John B. Judis’s 2000 book *The Paradox of American Democracy*.

The implementation was immediate and systematic. In March 1973, the Chamber of Commerce’s Public Affairs Committee convened a three-day conference at Disney World’s Polynesian Resort billed as the first gathering of the “Task Force on the Powell Memorandum.” Sessions focused on “enhancing the image of business,” strategies for political action, and creating a long-term framework to expand corporate influence — particularly how “the Chamber and business community can develop more political clout.” The task force divided into subcommittees, each focused on a core tenet of the memo: education, communications, political action, and judicial action. They were encouraged to think big, to “blue sky” their ideas beyond the memo’s already ambitious scope. By November 1974, the Committee on Business Overview — the permanent group born from the Powell Memo Task Force — had been implementing the memo’s recommendations for over a year.

The results were staggering in their scope and durability:

Within a decade of the memo’s release, the number of companies with public affairs offices in Washington increased from 100 to over 500. The number of companies with registered lobbyists rose from 175 to nearly 2,500. In 1971, there were only 176 companies in Washington, D.C. By 1980, there were 2,445 companies, 9,000 lobbyists, and 60,000 trade association employees.

The Heritage Foundation was established in 1973, funded initially by the Coors brewing family and Richard Mellon Scaife’s publishing enterprise. It marked the birth of a new type of politically aggressive and openly ideological “expert” organization. The Cato Institute followed. The American Enterprise Institute was revitalized. Together with over eighty large non-profit organizations — funded by a network of right-wing family foundations and wealthy individuals to the tune of $400 million a year — they formed what analyst Rob Stein called “the Big 80,” a conservative political movement that achieved a hammerlock on every aspect of federal government.

The Federalist Society, founded in 1982, began the systematic project of reshaping the federal judiciary. Powell himself had paved the doctrinal ground: his opinion in *First National Bank of Boston v. Bellotti* shifted the direction of First Amendment law by declaring that corporate financial influence of elections by independent expenditures should be protected with the same vigor as individual speech. This doctrinal seed grew, through decades of Federalist Society-cultivated judges and justices, into the Roberts Court’s decision in *Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission* — which broke radical new ground by striking down the edifice of campaign finance laws that had been erected precisely to prevent the kind of corporate political domination Powell had prescribed.

By the close of the 1970s, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce had been transformed from a cautious, passive business group into a politically aggressive and ideologically driven machine. It became part of the broader vision Powell had imagined: an alliance of business interests and conservative political groups, united in opposition to the regulatory state and working together as a social movement for capitalism. Measured in money spent, the Chamber became the most powerful lobby in Washington — $770.6 million since 1998, over three times the amount spent by the next-largest spender, General Electric. The Chamber reinforced its lobbying power by becoming one of the largest conduits of election-related “independent expenditures,” spending over $32.8 million on federal elections in 2010. It sponsors the Institute for Legal Reform, which spearheaded the campaign for tort “reform” — making it more difficult for people who have been injured, assaulted, or harmed to sue the responsible corporations. Along with well over a dozen legal foundations, the Chamber helped shape the powerful “business civil liberties” movement that was a driving force behind *Citizens United* and other judicial actions that handcuffed regulators and prevented Congress from putting common-sense checks on corporate power.

Charles Koch read the memo and concluded it didn’t go far enough. In a speech to the Institute for Humane Studies, which he had taken over in the early 1970s, Koch argued that Powell was wrong in assuming that most businesses believed in “free enterprise” — because Koch’s definition of that term was narrower still. He rejected the idea of equal opportunity laws, wage rules, and health and safety laws, framing them as inherently anti-capitalist, anti-free-market. He didn’t believe the business community was actually committed to free enterprise because it was willing to go along with common-sense regulations that the people wanted. Koch operationalized Powell’s vision over the intervening decades with a harder edge and deeper pockets. As journalist Nancy MacLean documented, the campaign amounted to a sustained effort to “save capitalism from democracy — permanently.” As Jane Mayer traced in *Dark Money*, a right-wing dark money network financed over the decades by magnates from Bryce Harlow to Richard Mellon Scaife to Joseph Coors funded think tanks, media outlets and writers, college programs, legal organizations, and politicians dedicated to advancing pro-business causes. The strategy worked: megacorporations now enjoy fewer regulations, lower taxes, more lobbyists, more businesspeople in power, and the ability to impede any policy perceived as hurting their bottom line, whether climate protections or health care reform.

Lisa Graves, a researcher who studied the memo’s impact, stated: “This document was not a product of the democratic process, but it has had a profound impact on our process by pushing forward a structure for how corporations can exert more influence on American life.”

The Powell Memo’s most consequential legacy is not any single institution it produced. It is the ecosystem — the flywheel of compounding institutional power. A Heritage Foundation policy paper becomes a Federalist Society legal brief becomes a Supreme Court opinion becomes a media talking point becomes a campaign contribution becomes a legislative outcome. Each component reinforces the others. Each year’s investment compounds into the next year’s capacity. More than 50 years after Powell’s memo, the Heritage Foundation — the same organization born from his vision — produced Project 2025, a 900-page manual for transforming the executive branch. The through-line is direct, documented, and unbroken.

Powell did not call for surveillance of citizens. He called for surveillance of media, textbooks, and universities — the institutional spaces where public opinion was formed. His project was to ensure that those spaces produced opinion favorable to corporate interests. The irony that would take fifty years to fully materialize is that the institutional architecture he built — the deregulated marketplace, the captured judiciary, the weakened regulatory agencies, the blocked privacy legislation — would create the precise conditions under which a surveillance apparatus emerged that made his original project look quaint. Powell wanted to monitor television. His heirs built a system that monitors everyone, all the time, and sells the data to the government without a warrant.

