## II. The Loophole

The United States does not have a comprehensive federal data privacy law. This is not an oversight. It is not regulatory lag. It is the downstream product of the regulatory vacuum that Powell’s institutional project created and sustained across five decades.

The contrast with the European Union is foundational. The GDPR, implemented in 2018, requires explicit and informed consent before personal data is collected. It applies to any entity that processes personal data in the context of activities in the EU or that targets EU individuals — without revenue thresholds, without processing thresholds, without broker thresholds. Violations carry administrative fines of up to €20 million or 4% of total worldwide annual turnover, whichever is higher. The GDPR defines personal data broadly: any information relating to an identified or identifiable natural person. It grants the “right to be forgotten.” It requires data portability. It restricts processing.

The United States, by contrast, has no single, comprehensive federal data privacy law. Instead, data privacy regulations are a combination of sector-specific and state-level laws that govern how personal data is collected, processed, and shared — varying in scope and enforcement and often focusing on specific industries such as healthcare, finance, and education. As of 2026, only four states — California, Oregon, Texas, and Vermont — require data brokers to register with state agencies and disclose their activities. The Consumer Financial Protection Bureau proposed a rule in December 2024 to limit the sale of sensitive personal information — Social Security numbers, phone numbers — under its interpretation of the Fair Credit Reporting Act. The CFPB ultimately concluded that such a rule was “not necessary or appropriate at this time.”

In the CCPA (California Consumer Privacy Act), for example, privacy enforcement relies on an opt-out model rather than the GDPR’s opt-in requirement: personal data can be collected and used without prior consent in most states, and the main legal requirement is simply that data subjects be informed about processing and their rights. The consequences of noncompliance reflect the gap: CCPA violators face civil penalties of up to $7,500 per intentional violation. The GDPR’s penalties can reach into the billions.

This patchwork is not accidental. It is what the absence of comprehensive federal legislation looks like — and that absence is maintained by the same lobbying infrastructure that the Powell Memo constructed. The Consumer Technology Association, in a letter to Congress, advocated for federal preemption of state privacy laws, no private right of action, and tiered compliance obligations — and criticized regulatory models based on the GDPR, warning they would “stifle innovation and harm smaller firms.” Senator Amy Klobuchar lamented that she had worked for years on federal privacy legislation without success.

And at the center of this patchwork is the gap that matters most: there is no federal law prohibiting law enforcement agencies from purchasing data that they would otherwise need a warrant to obtain.

This is the data broker loophole.

The Supreme Court’s 2018 decision in *Carpenter v. United States* held that police need a warrant to obtain historical cell-site location information. The Court recognized that tracking a person’s movements over time is extremely invasive, that individuals have a reasonable expectation of privacy in the “all-encompassing record” of their whereabouts. The Court wrote that such data gave the government “near perfect surveillance and allows it to travel back in time to retrace a person’s whereabouts, subject only to the five-year retention policies of most wireless carriers.” The holding was clear: Americans have a privacy right to their historical cell phone data, and it should be protected by, at minimum, a warrant requirement.

Federal agencies have argued that the *Carpenter* decision applies only to the specific type of location data at issue — cell-site location information compelled from telecommunications companies — and that Fourth Amendment protections apply only when the government *compels* disclosure, not when private companies *sell* or *voluntarily disclose* information to law enforcement. Based on these purported distinctions, agencies have continued to purchase cell phone location data — without a warrant or any other legal process — in large volumes. The government’s position is that buying data is constitutionally different from seizing it.

As the Brennan Center documented: “Unlike private entities, government agencies may purchase personal data to further their exercise of coercive powers, including the ability to deport, arrest, incarcerate, or even use lethal force. Unfettered government access to personal data without judicial or legislative oversight can exacerbate existing biases in law enforcement and intelligence practices, permitting speculative investigations on the basis of constitutionally protected categories and the targeting of marginalized communities.”

The evidence of this targeting is specific and documented:

The Department of Defense purchased location data from Muslim prayer and Qur’an apps and dating apps through defense contractors. A data broker named X-Mode compiled geolocation data from the Muslim prayer app Muslim Pro and the Muslim dating app Muslim Mingle, then sold this extremely sensitive data to the U.S. military through defense contractors.

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement began purchasing access to cell phone location data through a data brokerage company called Venntel in 2018. The data had been collected from popular cell phone apps — weather, shopping, and video game apps. ICE used Venntel’s service to track the movements of cell phone users near the southern border. At one point, ICE discovered phones moving back and forth across a closed portion of the border in a straight line — eventually determining they were traveling through an underground smuggling tunnel from a private home in Mexico to a closed Kentucky Fried Chicken restaurant in San Luis, Arizona. ICE passed this information to the local police department, which made an apparently pretextual traffic stop, finding large quantities of drugs. The San Luis police kept any mention of the cell phone tracking out of their records and initially attributed the stop to an “equipment violation.” This pattern — government agents obscuring their purchases of constitutionally protected information by recreating the data through more traditional means — raises concerns about deception, the avoidance of public scrutiny, and the denial of courts any opportunity to review the legality of the surveillance.

The FBI renegotiated its purchase contract with a data broker around the time of the Black Lives Matter demonstrations in 2020. Cell phone data was allegedly used to track protesters. As the Brennan Center noted, the use of purchased data to target religious groups and protesters emphasizes the critical importance of the Fourth Amendment in protecting against discriminatory policing and underscores the chilling effect unrestricted surveillance has on religious freedom and the right to dissent.

The IRS’s Criminal Investigations Division partnered with Venntel to identify and monitor potential criminal suspects.

Some police departments have attempted to circumvent bans on their use of facial recognition by purchasing facial recognition search results from third-party vendors — a technique that parallels the data broker loophole.

At the local level, the EFF’s investigation of Fog Data Science revealed a company that claims to collect 15 billion data points daily from 250 million U.S. devices every month, sourced from “tens of thousands” of mobile apps with tracking code included. Fog sells subscriptions to its Fog Reveal search engine — and does not require law enforcement to obtain a warrant or subpoena before searching. This gives police an easy way to pull up location records for a device and track and identify the device owner from their home address and place of work. The EFF filed over 100 public records requests and discovered at least 18 agencies with past or ongoing contractual relationships with Fog. In Chino, California, police used Fog’s service for massive sweeps determining who was near minor theft and burglary scenes. In rural Missouri, police built an extensive movement profile of a murder victim’s babysitter — who was never a suspect. In Greensboro, North Carolina, a crime analysis supervisor raised red flags about constitutionality and later quit after his warnings were ignored. In none of these cases were policies or limits governing use documented in the public records.

Location records from brokers are typically unlinked to a device owner’s name. But tools exist that help law enforcement track where a device has gone, where it spends every night, and where it goes during working hours. As EFF staff technologist Bill Budington noted, it doesn’t take much police work to link “anonymized” data — timestamps, location coordinates, and advertising IDs — to actual people. In post-*Roe* America, this means law enforcement can bypass warrants for Google Maps queries to build a case against an individual seeking an abortion in a state where the procedure is illegal.

EFF investigator Beryl Lipton stated: “Police departments of all sizes have been using a system that stores and makes searchable the historical locations of individuals. This means that they could identify the phones — and, by extension, the people — that have been at a protest, a reproductive health center, a place of worship, or other locations and track them to the places they live. This violates our constitutional rights, especially when police do it without a warrant.”

Anthropic CEO Dario Amodei warned in a February 2026 statement that records the government can purchase can be used by AI to assemble “a comprehensive picture of any person’s life — automatically and at massive scale.” His unwillingness to allow Anthropic’s technology to be used for domestic mass surveillance or autonomous weapons led to a confrontation with the Pentagon, which responded that a private company cannot dictate how the government lawfully uses its technology. Anthropic was designated a supply chain risk.

When Senator Ron Wyden asked FBI Director Kash Patel in early 2026 whether the Bureau would commit to not buying Americans’ location data, Patel declined, saying the FBI “uses all tools” and purchases “commercially available information that’s consistent with the Constitution and the laws under the Electronic Communications Privacy Act.”

Privacy advocate Jake Laperruque of the Center for Democracy and Technology noted that purchasing bulk data from data brokers is “very much not what Congress intended when it said we are banning bulk collection. It wasn’t, ‘do bulk collection, but also pay taxpayer money for it.’ It was ‘don’t do bulk collection.’” He added that the idea that law enforcement can purchase information from data brokers they would normally need a warrant for doesn’t make sense — particularly since it is often possible to identify individuals from supposedly anonymized data.

The surveillance society expert Jeramie D. Scott, senior counsel at the Electronic Privacy Information Center, told NPR that government data purchases without a warrant are “contributing to an ever-expanding infrastructure of private sector surveillance that is hurtling us into a dystopian surveillance society.”

Montana became the first state to close the data broker loophole for law enforcement in May 2025, prohibiting police from purchasing citizens’ data when they would ordinarily need a warrant. The bipartisan Fourth Amendment Is Not For Sale Act passed the House in 2024 with near-unanimous Judiciary Committee support. The Brennan Center, the Project on Government Oversight, and over 130 civil society organizations urged Congress to include closure of the loophole in FISA Section 702 reauthorization, citing the “unprecedented expansion of warrantless mass surveillance that is sweeping up the private information of communities across America” and the potential for the loophole to be used “to supercharge AI-powered surveillance.”

Representative Warren Davidson (R-Ohio) told NPR that this “doesn’t break on party lines” — “You’re collecting data that really you would never get a warrant for, that kind of a broad dragnet sweep under normal warrant requirements.” He teamed up with conservative Senator Mike Lee and Democrats Zoe Lofgren and Wyden on bicameral bipartisan reform legislation. The coalition exists. The legislation exists. As of April 2026, Congress has not acted.

