## III. The Convergence Abroad

If the American trajectory is the product of the Powell Memo’s institutional capture, the global trajectory reveals a convergence across political systems that defies the stated justifications of each but produces the same material outcome.

**The European Retreat.** The GDPR was the most comprehensive privacy framework in the world — the model that influenced legislation from Brazil to India to California. For a decade, it served as the democratic counterweight to the American surveillance model.

In November 2025, the European Commission published the Digital Omnibus — a package of reforms to the GDPR, the ePrivacy Directive, and the AI Act, presented as simplification for small and medium enterprises. European Digital Rights described it as “a massive reopening of EU’s core digital protections — a move that risks dismantling the very foundation of human rights and tech policy in the EU.” The EFF called it a proposal that “promises red tape cuts but guts GDPR privacy rights” and noted that while the GDPR “is the most comprehensive model for privacy legislation around the world” and “far from perfect,” the Omnibus “is full of bad and confusing ideas that, on balance, will significantly weaken privacy protections for users in the name of cutting red tape.” Amnesty International described it as a “coordinated effort to weaken corporate accountability,” noting the false dichotomy between regulation and innovation “championed by Big Tech, who seek a rules-free environment that prioritizes profit at any cost.” Amnesty further noted that “pressure is mounting across different areas of regulation, resulting in the rolling back of environmental protections, the weakening of corporate governance and erosion of digital rights. It all amounts to a coordinated effort to weaken corporate accountability.”

The European Data Protection Board and the European Data Protection Supervisor issued a joint opinion “strongly urging the co-legislators not to adopt the proposed changes to the definition of personal data as they go far beyond a targeted or technical amendment of the GDPR.” They warned that the changes “do not accurately reflect and clearly go beyond the CJEU jurisprudence, and they would result in significantly narrowing the concept of personal data.” They specifically warned that “the European Commission should not be entrusted to decide by an implementing act what is no longer personal data after pseudonymisation as it directly affects the scope of application of EU data protection law.”

The proposed changes would narrow the definition of personal data — meaning pseudonymous identifiers like ad IDs and cookies could lose GDPR protection, paving the way for more tracking and profiling. A new “legitimate interest” exception would allow companies to use personal data, including some sensitive information, for AI training without explicit consent. Under these rules, high-risk AI systems could process massive amounts of European data legally while traditional data storage and processing remain tightly regulated. The privacy NGO noyb warned this could give U.S. and global tech companies freer rein to use European data for AI training or analytics — and that EU users would rarely know their data was being used, with objections nearly impossible to enforce.

The ePrivacy framework — governing how companies access data on users’ devices — would be absorbed into the GDPR under conditions that shift Europe from an opt-in system to something closer to opt-out. Article 22, which limits automated decision-making, would be reframed as a broader permission for automation — turning what the Digital Omnibus critics describe as “a prohibition with exceptions into an authorisation subject to conditions,” making it easier to deploy automated systems in contexts where human review currently matters and harder for people to challenge decisions that significantly affect their lives.

The Digital Omnibus on AI tears the AI Act apart, undermining key protections including oversight and transparency mechanisms. Those making or selling AI systems could exempt themselves from fundamental rules. It delays the high-risk requirements without a clear timeline and subverts protections for people from AI harms.

Technologist Robin Berjon warned: “We’ve seen the European Commission be weak on enforcement and hesitant to anger the American authorities, but the omnibus changes go much further. American tech monopolies and intelligence agencies are the biggest beneficiaries of the surveillance economy and these changes strengthen their hand to instead actively sabotage European businesses and national security.”

The Commission’s Executive Vice President met with top U.S. tech executives to pitch a more business-friendly Europe. The reforms followed Mario Draghi’s report warning that Europe’s complex laws were stifling innovation. The language of competitiveness — the same rhetorical framework that the Powell project deployed against American regulation fifty years ago — is now being used to dismantle the one democratic privacy framework that had achieved meaningful protection at scale.

Even the existing GDPR has structural gaps in its coverage of data brokers. As Lawfare documented, the GDPR framework “can leave both legal and conceptual gaps when it comes to weighing the role that other, less directly consumer-connected parties gather, process, generate, and transmit data, such as the potential lack of GDPR coverage when one broker sells data it did not collect itself to another data broker.” The inferences that data brokers create and sell — using location data to derive information about military service or children in the home — “can also receive inadequate coverage under data protection law.” European regulators, focused overwhelmingly on American Big Tech companies like Meta and Alphabet, have paid less attention to data brokerage operating within Europe. An RTÉ investigation in Ireland found reporters could gain access to brokered data on tens of thousands of smartphones that could trace devices between residential addresses, high-security prisons, health clinics, mental health facilities, military bases, and the Irish parliament.

If the GDPR is hollowed out through the Digital Omnibus, there is no major democratic government on earth with a comprehensive framework strong enough to matter. Brazil’s LGPD, India’s DPDP Act, and the other frameworks modeled on the GDPR lose their conceptual anchor.

**China and India.** Ralph Schroeder’s research at Oxford identifies China’s Social Credit System and India’s Aadhaar as “two cases of the most rapid capture of personal data about national populations in history.” Both governments claim participation is voluntary while linking vital services to registration. Both raise concerns about mass surveillance and technocratic governance. Both demonstrate what scholars at the Institute of Chinese Studies describe as “the potential dangers of ‘big data’ in ushering a surveillance state apparatus and the existence of blurred boundaries between democracy and authoritarianism when it comes to social control.”

China’s Social Credit System aims to establish a “sincerity culture” by rating trustworthiness and providing benefits to the trustworthy while punishing the untrustworthy. In 2024, the NDRC issued plans for more complete credit legislation, unified codes, and strengthened platform infrastructure. In March 2025, Party-and-State Council guidelines targeted improvement of the system with 23 measures, stressing safeguards around information security, individual rights, and guarding against excessive collection — a tacit acknowledgment that excessive collection is the default. Over 200 million surveillance cameras, augmented by AI facial recognition, are deployed. The government tracks online behavior. While the system is not the monolithic unified scoring mechanism Western media sometimes portrays — it remains fragmented between localities, and entries are still manually entered by officials — it represents the explicit integration of behavioral surveillance into governance at a scale unprecedented in human history.

India’s Aadhaar — the world’s largest biometric identification system — issues a 12-digit number to every resident, generated after recording demographic and biometric data including fingerprints and iris scans. Launched in 2009 as a voluntary system to deliver welfare benefits, it now covers 99% of the population. Despite claiming participation was voluntary, the Indian government made Aadhaar mandatory for citizens to access bank accounts, insurance policies, and tax payments — while even by 2017 there were hardly any legislative measures to protect the data being collected. Intelligence officials acknowledged that the welfare claim was partly a pretext — the system’s purpose included flushing out illegal immigrants. Security officials made attempts to use the Aadhaar database to identify “criminals,” and researchers documented that news coverage in India largely disregarded the public interest and focused on how businesses could benefit, showing little concern with violations of privacy and mass surveillance.

Saif Shahin and Pei Zheng’s research argued that this media framing “renders citizens structurally incapable of making” informed choices about participation — because the information environment itself has been shaped to preclude informed dissent.

The justifications differ across systems. The United States deregulates in the name of market freedom. The European Union deregulates in the name of competitiveness. China builds social credit in the name of social harmony. India deploys Aadhaar in the name of financial inclusion. The trajectory is identical: states and corporations accumulating unprecedented surveillance capacity over populations with diminishing oversight. The distinction between a democratic government purchasing your location data from a broker and an authoritarian government collecting it directly is a distinction of method, not of outcome. The citizen is rendered transparent. The state is rendered opaque. The asymmetry is the same.

